---

<BlogArticleLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  breadcrumbItems={[
    { label: 'Home', href: '/' },
    { label: 'Resources', href: '/resources' },
    { label: 'Glossary', href: '/resources/glossary' },
    { label: 'Academic acronyms glossary' },
  ]}
  heroLabel="Glossary"
  heroSubtitle={description}
  updatedDate={`Updated ${updatedDate}`}
  readingTime={readingTime}
  author={author}
  tags={[
    'Glossary',
    'Degrees',
    'Nursing',
    'Information technology',
    'Accreditation',
    'Higher education',
  ]}
  heroImage={heroImageUrl}
  image={heroImageUrl}
  tocItems={tocItems}
  canonical={canonicalPath}
>
  <Fragment slot="schema">
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(articleSchema)} />
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(breadcrumbSchema)} />
  </Fragment>

  <ArticleProse>
    <p class="article-intro">
      Academic acronyms can be confusing because colleges, universities, accrediting agencies, and
      professional fields often use different shorthand for the same type of credential or program.
      This glossary brings together common degree abbreviations, nursing acronyms, IT terms, and
      accreditation language in one easy-to-scan reference.
    </p>

    <section id="degree-abbreviations">
      <h2>Degree abbreviations</h2>
      <p>
        These are some of the most common academic degree abbreviations used in the United States.
        Some schools and style guides use slightly different punctuation or formatting, but the
        meanings are generally consistent.
      </p>

      <div class="data-table">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th scope="col">Acronym</th>
              <th scope="col">Meaning</th>
              <th scope="col">Common use</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>AA</td>
              <td>Associate of Arts</td>
              <td>Two-year degree in liberal arts or humanities.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>AAS</td>
              <td>Associate of Applied Science</td>
              <td>Career-focused associate degree.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>ADN</td>
              <td>Associate Degree in Nursing</td>
              <td>Entry-level nursing degree.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>ASN</td>
              <td>Associate of Science in Nursing</td>
              <td>Nursing-focused associate degree.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>AS</td>
              <td>Associate of Science</td>
              <td>Two-year degree in science or technical fields.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>ASc</td>
              <td>Associate of Science</td>
              <td>Variant styling used by some schools.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>BA</td>
              <td>Bachelor of Arts</td>
              <td>Undergraduate degree in liberal arts.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>BS</td>
              <td>Bachelor of Science</td>
              <td>Undergraduate degree in science or technical fields.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>BSc</td>
              <td>Bachelor of Science</td>
              <td>Common alternate styling, often used internationally and sometimes in U.S. writing.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>BSN</td>
              <td>Bachelor of Science in Nursing</td>
              <td>Standard pre-licensure nursing degree.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>BBA</td>
              <td>Bachelor of Business Administration</td>
              <td>Business-focused undergraduate degree.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>BFA</td>
              <td>Bachelor of Fine Arts</td>
              <td>Arts-focused undergraduate degree.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
