              <td>Preferred nursing degree in many healthcare settings.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>MSN</td>
              <td>Master of Science in Nursing</td>
              <td>Graduate-level nursing degree.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>DNP</td>
              <td>Doctor of Nursing Practice</td>
              <td>Highest clinical nursing degree in many settings.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h3>Nursing degree hierarchy</h3>
      <p>
        Many students begin with an associate-level nursing degree and later move into a BSN or MSN
        pathway. Employers may prefer a BSN for leadership, hospital, or specialty roles, while
        graduate degrees such as MSN and DNP support advanced practice and teaching. For search
        visibility, it helps to include both the acronym and the full title in the same entry.
      </p>
    </section>

